AGI&nbsp; - What does solidarity do? In Rome, tonight, Cristina's smile. Luca's look. Martina's curly hair. They are the volunteers who have chosen to join the 'Night of Solidarity', the initiative promoted by the Department of Social Policies of Rome Capital with the National Institute of Statistics to cense the population without abode in the municipal territory of Rome. To make possible the census, the volunteers who chose to join by registering through the portal dedicated to the event. An initiative that has seen in particular the participation of young people, according to the numbers announced during the press point carried out in evening in Capitol.
&nbsp;
More than 700 young university students on a total of 1962 enrolled, including 1657 volunteers. 62 percent of the abductions came from women, 37 percent from men, 795 are university students and 328 volunteers over 60. Six universities involved, 36 member bodies and 127 bodies involved. All those who responded to the call for solidarity have been organized in teams, divided into 20 clusters and 338 areas, and, right in these hours and throughout the evening of Saturday, April 20, are collaborating to the survey with the aim to identify and count the people without roof, who live on the street, in lucky accommodation or in dorms and in the reception facilities.
&nbsp;
36 associations including the Red Cross, the community of Sant'Egidio, Angels on two wheels, Mother Rome. Common objective, "to make a city that includes and does not want to leave anyone on the margins" as explained by Barbara Funari, Councillor for the Social Policies of Rome Capital during the press point organized in Capitol. "Rome is a leader, 14 other cities will follow this model," explained the city council member.
&nbsp;
"This participation of young people is, in particular, very important - Funari added -, they told us that it is the first time they approach and meet a person who lives in the street. Sometimes you think they are experiences far away from us, but then you find that so many people like us can end up in the street. This shows that the participation of young people is possible, unlike what is often said." Capital is the first to join the project, launched by Istat, then will follow 14 cities. "We, like Rome, welcomed the challenge of starting first. The next cities will be able to take inspiration from our example and follow us as a model. Rome is the capital of solidarity, we are proud to be able to say it."&nbsp;
&nbsp;
The mayor of Rome, Roberto Gualtieri, explained that with the night of the solidarity of Rome "an initiative of important knowledge is realized for two reasons. First, you go beyond the size of the center and cover the whole ring area, then the consolidated size of the city. The phenomenon of people in difficulty does not only concern the places of which we talk most often. Many times the homeless are considered problems and not people in difficulty. You can not intervene without knowing - the mayor has continued - Rome must support the people in difficulty but if you do not know it can not do it. This is an attempt to know people and understand how we can do to help them better and give them a roof and integration path.&nbsp; Our work is to build paths that invest in integration strategies, support and support that will give these people a path of autonomy. They are not numbers - Gualtieri has concluded - they are people who are to be known and they are to be looked in the eyes". &nbsp;
&nbsp;
"The direct impact with the most fragile was not easy, but even more difficult was to overturn some roles and visions - it was the passionate story of Cristina, student of the University of Tor Vergata, who brought her own testimony -&nbsp; we had the burden and honor to enter the tip of feet in the life of these people who, contrary to what you think, have the desire to feel and feel. We didn't just mention statistics, but whole lives."
&nbsp;
"The night of solidarity allowed us to grow humanly - Christian concluded -. Our hope is that the number of participants will continue to grow. This is the army we like," he concluded, addressing volunteers.
